text:
Phil Mickelson turned 50 in June and Tiger Woods will turn 45 in December. They still would command large crowds, if crowds were allowed, but popularity doesn’t translate to low scores. Golf doesn’t bow to reputation, writes @RonKroichick.

text: As of Thursday there were nearly 70 reported cases of the coronavirus in the state’s three youth prisons — or about 9% of the current population. More than a dozen staff had also tested positive for the virus. https://t.co/ZuLRbGLXXg

text: Latino businesses have been hit particularly hard by the pandemic — the number of Latino business owners whose firms were active dropped 43% from the beginning of February to the end of April, compared with a 19% drop in white owners of active businesses. https://t.co/y42sw1fDk5

name: sfchronicle
text: Hospitals in California are caring for 5,746 COVID-19 patients, continuing a downward trend, state officials reported. Of those hospitalized, 1,868 are in ICUs. Bay Area hospitalizations have also been trending down, standing at 663 patients on Friday. https://t.co/5QSt6VPc4l
